# Linux Access Control Lists (ACL) Reference Guide

A comprehensive cheat sheet and technical guide for configuring granular file system permissions in Linux using Access Control Lists (ACL).

---

## 1. Introduction to Linux ACL

In standard Linux security, file permissions are bound to the traditional **UGO (User, Group, Others)** ownership model managed via `chmod` and `chown`. While highly efficient, UGO permissions fall short when multiple individual users or distinct groups require different levels of access to the exact same file system object.

**Access Control Lists (ACL)** overcome this barrier by providing a flexible mechanism to inject precise, granular permissions. With ACLs, system administrators can explicitly define permission sets for any arbitrary user or group without changing primary ownership or altering broader system-wide configurations.

---

## 2. Core ACL Types

Linux classifies Access Control Lists into two main operational categories:

* **Access ACLs:** Applied directly to specific files or directories to dictate active permissions for real-time operations on existing objects.
* **Default ACLs:** Assigned exclusively to *directories*. They do not alter access permissions for the directory itself; instead, they serve as a dynamic template. Any newly created file or sub-directory within that path automatically inherits these predefined permission rules.

---

## 3. Essential Commands & Examples

The primary utilities for interacting with ACLs are `getfacl` (to audit permissions) and `setfacl` (to modify or remove permissions).

| Command Syntax | Action & Technical Description |
| :--- | :--- |
| `setfacl -m u:lisa:rwx FILE_PATH` | **Grant User Access:** Adds or overrides an Access ACL entry for the specific user `lisa`, granting full Read (`r`), Write (`w`), and Execute (`x`) permissions on the target file. |
| `setfacl -x u:lisa FILE_PATH` | **Remove User ACL Entry:** Drops the user-specific ACL rule for `lisa` from the target file. Access reverts back to standard group or 'other' permission scopes. |
| `setfacl -m d:u:harry:rwx DIR_PATH` | **Configure Default ACL:** Applies an inheritance template to a directory. All future child files and sub-folders created inside `DIR_PATH` will automatically inherit full `rwx` rights for user `harry`. |
| `setfacl -b FILE_PATH` | **Purge All Extended ACLs:** Strips away all extended user, group, and default ACL mappings, resetting the object purely to standard UGO permissions. |
| `setfacl -k DIR_PATH` | **Delete Default Template:** Removes the Default ACL layer from a directory, stopping inheritance for future child objects without affecting files that already exist. |

---

## 4. Quick Flag Reference

When constructing `setfacl` commands, understand the core operational flags to prevent structural configuration errors:

* `-m` (**modify**) : Used to add a new ACL rule or adjust an existing rule.
* `-x` (**remove**) : Used to extract and delete a precise user or group rule.
* `-b` (**remove-all**) : Completely deletes all extended rules, completely wiping custom ACL metadata.
* `-k` (**remove-default**) : Isolates and deletes only the dynamic inheritance layer on directories.

> 💡 **Pro Tip for Git/GitHub:** Standard Git repositories do not preserve Linux extended ACL metadata when files are committed. If your deployment environment requires these permissions, it is best practice to include a baseline shell script (e.g., `apply_acls.sh`) containing these commands within your repository to run during CI/CD pipelines or provisioning steps.

---

## 5. Auditing Mappings with `getfacl`

To inspect active ACL mappings on any system object, use the `getfacl` command:

```bash
$ getfacl example_file.txt
# file: example_file.txt
# owner: root
# group: root
user::rw-
user:lisa:rwx   # Extended ACL rule active
group::r--
mask::rwx
other::r--
